class CNNWrapper(pl.LightningModule):
    def __init__(self, model, model_name, fold, loss_fn=nn.CrossEntropyLoss(),
                 optimizer=optim.AdamW, learning_rate=1e-3):
        super(CNNWrapper, self).__init__()
        
        self.model = model.to(device)
        self.optimizer = optimizer(model.parameters(), lr=learning_rate)
        self.learning_rate = learning_rate
        self.loss_fn = loss_fn
        
        self.model_name = model_name
        self.fold = fold
    
    def forward(self, x):
        return self.model(x)
    
    def training_step(self, batch, batch_idx):
        inputs, labels = batch
        outputs = self.model(inputs)
        loss = self.loss_fn(outputs, labels)
        
        acc = (labels==outputs.argmax(axis=1)).sum().item() / labels.shape[0]
        
        run[f'{self.model_name}/fold{self.fold}/train/loss'].append(loss.item())
        run[f'{self.model_name}/fold{self.fold}/train/accuracy'].append(acc) 
        if batch_idx % 10 == 0:
            print(f'batch: {batch_idx} ({(batch_idx + 1) * inputs.shape[0]} samples), loss = {loss:.3f}')
        
        return loss
    
    def validation_step(self, batch, batch_idx):
        inputs, labels = batch
        outputs = self.model(inputs)
        loss = self.loss_fn(outputs, labels)

        acc = (labels==outputs.argmax(axis=1)).sum().item() / labels.shape[0]
        
        self.log("val_acc", acc)
        self.log('val_loss',loss.item())
        
        run[f'{self.model_name}/fold{self.fold}/validation/loss'].append(loss.item())
        run[f'{self.model_name}/fold{self.fold}/validation/accuracy'].append(acc)
        
        return loss
    
    def configure_optimizers(self):
        return self.optimizer

@torch.no_grad()
def test_loop(model, data_loader):
    model.eval()
    model.to(device)
    
    results = {
        'loss': [],
        'acc': [],
        'preds': [], 
        'lables':[]
    }
    for imgs, labels in data_loader:
        imgs, labels = imgs.to(device), labels.to(device)
        
        outputs = model(imgs)
        loss = hp['criteria'](outputs, labels).item()
        probs, preds = torch.max(torch.softmax(outputs, dim=1), dim=1)
        acc = (preds == labels).sum().item() / labels.size(0) 
        
        results['lables'].append(labels)
        results['loss'].append(loss)
        results['acc'].append(acc)
        results['preds'].append(preds)
    
    return results

def move_samples(src_folder, dest_folder, class_folders, split_ratio):
    for class_folder in class_folders:
        class_path = os.path.join(src_folder, class_folder)
        images = os.listdir(class_path)
        num_samples = len(images)
        
        num_samples_to_move = int(num_samples * split_ratio)
        
        samples_to_move = random.sample(images, num_samples_to_move)
        
        for sample in samples_to_move:
            src_path = os.path.join(class_path, sample)
            dest_path = os.path.join(dest_folder, class_folder, 'train-' + sample)
            shutil.move(src_path, dest_path)

In [16]:
class CNNBlock(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, in_channels, out_channels, kernel_size,
                 two_convs=False, use_batchnorm=False):
        super(CNNBlock, self).__init__()
        self.two_convs = two_convs
        self.use_bn = use_batchnorm
        
        self.conv = nn.Conv2d(in_channels, out_channels, kernel_size, padding='same')
        self.relu = nn.ReLU()
        
        if two_convs:
            self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(out_channels, out_channels, kernel_size, padding='same')
            self.relu2 = nn.ReLU()

        self.max_pool = nn.MaxPool2d(2, 2)
        if use_batchnorm:
            self.bn = nn.BatchNorm2d(out_channels)
    
    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.conv(x)
        x = self.relu(x)
        
        if self.two_convs:
            x = self.conv2(x)
            x = self.relu2(x)
        
        x = self.max_pool(x)
        if self.use_bn:
            x = self.bn(x)
            
        return x
In [17]:
class FishCNN(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, num_classes, in_channels=3, kernel_size=3,
                 two_convs=False, use_batchnorm=False):
        super(FishCNN, self).__init__()

        blocks = [CNNBlock(in_channels, 32, kernel_size, two_convs, use_batchnorm)]
        blocks += [CNNBlock(2**(i-1), 2**(i), kernel_size, two_convs, use_batchnorm)
                   for i in range(6, 9)]
        self.blocks = nn.ModuleList(blocks)

        self.linear = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(256 * 14 * 14, 1024),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(1024, num_classes)
        )
        
    def forward(self, x):
        for block in self.blocks:
            x = block(x)
        x = x.view(x.size(0), -1)
        x = self.linear(x)

        return x

Training¶

In [19]:
if train:
    num_classes = hp['num_classes']
    lr = hp['learning_rate']
    max_epochs = hp['max_epochs']
    k_folds = hp['num_folds']
    criteria = hp['criteria']
    optimizer = hp['optimizer']

    for (filename, use_batchnorm, two_convs) in list(zip(hp['model_filename'],
                                                         hp['use_batchnorm'],
                                                         hp['two_convs'])):
        kf = KFold(n_splits=k_folds, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

        for fold, (train_idx, val_idx) in enumerate(kf.split(dataset)):
            train_dataset = Subset(dataset, train_idx)
            val_dataset = Subset(dataset, val_idx)

            train_loader = DataLoader(train_dataset, batch_size=64, shuffle=True, num_workers=3)
            val_loader = DataLoader(val_dataset, batch_size=64, num_workers=3)

            cnn = FishCNN(num_classes=num_classes, two_convs=two_convs,
                          use_batchnorm=use_batchnorm)
            model = CNNWrapper(cnn, filename, fold,
                               loss_fn=criteria, optimizer=optimizer, learning_rate=lr)

            trainer = pl.Trainer(
                accelerator='auto',
                devices=1,
                max_epochs=hp['max_epochs']
            )

            print(f'\n\nTraining fold #{fold + 1} of model {filename}')

            trainer.fit(model, train_dataloaders=train_loader, val_dataloaders=val_loader)

            torch.save(model.model.state_dict(), f'models/{filename}-fold{fold}.pt')

def vis_pred(model, dataloader, num_images=1, good_threshold=None, bad_threshold=None):
    model.eval()
    count_good = 0
    count_uncertain = 0
    count_bad = 0

    for images, labels in dataloader:
        images = images.to(device)  # Move input data to the same device as the model
        labels = labels.to(device)
        
        with torch.no_grad():
            outputs = model(images)
            probs, preds = torch.max(torch.softmax(outputs, dim=1), dim=1)
            
        for i in range(images.shape[0]):
            image = images[i].cpu().numpy().transpose((1, 2, 0))
            image = (image - image.min()) / (image.max() - image.min())

            pred = preds[i].item()
            true = labels[i].item()

            acc = (pred == true)

            if good_threshold is not None and acc and probs[i] >= good_threshold:
                title = f"Predicted: {pred}, True: {true}, Probability: {probs[i]:.2f}"
                if count_good < num_images:
                    plot_image(image, title)
                    count_good += 1

            elif bad_threshold is not None and not acc and probs[i] <= bad_threshold:
                title = f"Predicted: {pred}, True: {true}, Probability: {probs[i]:.2f}"
                if count_bad < num_images:
                    plot_image(image, title)
                    count_bad += 1

            elif good_threshold is not None and bad_threshold is not None:
                if probs[i] < good_threshold and probs[i] >= bad_threshold:
                    title = f"Predicted: {pred}, True: {true}, Probability: {probs[i]:.2f}"
                    if count_uncertain < num_images:
                        plot_image(image, title)
                        count_uncertain += 1

            if count_good == num_images and count_uncertain == num_images and count_bad == num_images:
                break

        if count_good == num_images and count_uncertain == num_images and count_bad == num_images:
            break
            
def plot_image(image, title):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    ax.imshow(image)
    ax.set_title(title)
    plt.show()
            
def top5_accuracy(model, dataloader,k=5):
    """
    Calculates top-5 accuracy for a PyTorch model.
    """

    num_correct = 0

    for inputs, labels in dataloader:
        inputs = inputs.to(device)
        labels = labels.to(device)
        outputs = model(inputs)
        _, top5 = outputs.topk(k, dim=1)
        num_correct += torch.sum(torch.eq(top5, labels.view(-1, 1))).item()

    top5_acc = num_correct / len(dataloader.dataset)

    return top5_acc

def evaluate_model(model, data_loader):
    device = torch.device('cuda' if torch.cuda.is_available() else 'cpu')
    model.eval()
    y_true = []
    y_pred = []

    with torch.no_grad():
        for inputs, labels in data_loader:
            inputs, labels = inputs.to(device), labels.to(device)
            outputs = model(inputs)
            _, predicted = torch.max(outputs, 1)
            y_true.extend(labels.cpu().numpy())
            y_pred.extend(predicted.cpu().numpy())

    confusion = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    precision = np.mean(confusion.diagonal() / confusion.sum(axis=0))
    recall = np.mean(confusion.diagonal() / confusion.sum(axis=1))
    
    return confusion, precision, recall

def plot_confusion_matrix(confusion_matrix, classes):
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    sns.set(font_scale=1.2)
    sns.heatmap(confusion_matrix, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues", xticklabels=classes, yticklabels=classes)
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Labels')
    plt.ylabel('True Labels')
    plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
    plt.show()

    plot_confusion_matrix(conf, test_dataset.classes)

It seems like the model is misclassifying samples with relatively high confidence. After reviewing the learning curves and the testing results, it appears that the model has gotten overfit with high certainty. We believe that the reason is that the model is too complex for the data and the task, and thus loses the generalization during the training process.


In order to solve this, we suggest 3 solutions:


    

  1. Add a strong regularization to the model (such as dropout)
    2. 

  2. Decrease the complexity of the model architecture by removing layers
    3. 

  3. Reduce the number of training epochs
    4. 



We will implement the first two.























Inference-Time-Augmentation¶


















In [28]:



     


def inference_time_augmentation(model, dataloader, num_augmentations=5):
    model.eval()
    all_predictions = []

    with torch.no_grad():
        for images, _ in dataloader:
            images = images.to(device)

            augmented_predictions = []
            for _ in range(num_augmentations):
                augmented_images = apply_augmentation(images)
                outputs = model(augmented_images)
                predictions = torch.softmax(outputs, dim=1)
                augmented_predictions.append(predictions.cpu().numpy())

            aggregated_predictions = torch.tensor(np.array(augmented_predictions)).mean(dim=0)
            all_predictions.append(aggregated_predictions)
            
    return torch.cat(all_predictions, dim=0)

def apply_augmentation(images):
    transform = transforms.Compose([
        transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip(),
        transforms.RandomVerticalFlip(),
        transforms.RandomRotation(10),
    ])

    augmented_images = torch.stack([transform(image) for image in images])
    return augmented_images.to(device)

def accuracy(predictions, targets):
    num_correct = np.sum(predictions == targets)
    num_total = len(targets)
    accuracy = float(num_correct) / float(num_total)
    return accuracy

if test:
    test_loader = DataLoader(test_dataset, batch_size=64, shuffle=False, num_workers=3)
    predictions = inference_time_augmentation(model, test_loader, num_augmentations=5)
    predictions = predictions.argmax(dim=1).cpu().numpy()
    targets = np.array(test_loader.dataset.targets)

    acc = accuracy(predictions, targets)
    print("Accuracy: {:.2f}%".format(acc*100))

Model enhancement¶


















In [29]:



     


class FishCNNEnhanced(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, num_classes, in_channels=3, kernel_size=3, dropout=0.3):
        super(FishCNNEnhanced, self).__init__()
        
        two_convs, use_batchnorm = True, True

        blocks = [CNNBlock(in_channels, 32, kernel_size, two_convs, use_batchnorm),
                  nn.Dropout(dropout)]
        for i in range(6, 8):
            blocks.append(CNNBlock(2**(i-1), 2**(i), kernel_size, two_convs, use_batchnorm))
            blocks.append(nn.Dropout(dropout))
            
        self.blocks = nn.ModuleList(blocks)

        self.linear = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(128 * 28 * 28, 1024),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(1024, num_classes)
        )
        
    def forward(self, x):
        for block in self.blocks:
            x = block(x)
        x = x.view(x.size(0), -1)
        x = self.linear(x)

        return x

if finetune:
    num_classes = hp['num_classes']
    lr = hp['learning_rate']
    max_epochs = 5
    criteria = hp['criteria']
    optimizer = hp['optimizer']
    final_results = {}

    for name, model in models_list.items():
        if name == 'densenet121':
            model.classifier = nn.Linear(model.classifier.in_features, num_classes)
        elif name == 'vgg16' or name == 'mobilenet_v2':
            model.classifier[-1] = nn.Linear(model.classifier[-1].in_features, num_classes)
        else:
            model.fc = nn.Linear(model.fc.in_features, num_classes)

        parameters = list(model.named_parameters())
        for idx, (_, param) in enumerate(parameters):
            if idx < len(parameters) - 2:
                param.requires_grad = False

        model = CNNWrapper(model , name, 'None',
                           loss_fn=criteria, optimizer=optimizer, learning_rate=lr)  

        trainer = pl.Trainer(
            accelerator='auto',
            devices=1,
            max_epochs=max_epochs, 
            callbacks=[
                ModelCheckpoint(save_weights_only=True, mode="min", monitor="val_loss"),
                LearningRateMonitor("epoch")
            ]
        )

        print(f'Training {name}')

        trainer.fit(model, train_dataloaders=train_loader, val_dataloaders=val_loader)

        parameters = list(model.named_parameters())
        for idx, (_, param) in enumerate(parameters):
                param.requires_grad = True

        trainer = pl.Trainer(
            accelerator='auto',
            devices=1,
            max_epochs=max_epochs//2,
            callbacks=[
                ModelCheckpoint(save_weights_only=True, mode="min", monitor="val_loss"),
                LearningRateMonitor("epoch")
            ]
        )

        trainer.fit(model, train_dataloaders=train_loader, val_dataloaders=val_loader)

        validation_metrics[name] = {
            'loss': trainer.callback_metrics['val_loss'].item(),
            'acc': trainer.callback_metrics['val_acc'].item()
        }

        torch.save(model.model.state_dict(), f'{name}.pt')

def uniques(models_preds, labels):
    c_e = torch.stack([preds == labels for preds in models_preds], dim=0)  # (# models, # preds)

    n_unique = []
    for i in range(len(c_e)):
        unique_correct = ((c_e.sum(axis=0) == 1) & c_e[i]).sum().item()
        unique_false = ((c_e.sum(axis=0) == c_e.shape[0] - 1) & ~c_e[i]).sum().item()
        n_unique.append((unique_correct, unique_false))
    
    return n_unique

Using Pretrained Models as Feature-Extractor:¶


















In [46]:



     


@torch.no_grad()
def extract_features(model, dataloader):
    model.eval()

    features, labels = [], []
    for inputs, targets in tqdm(dataloader, desc="Feature extraction"):
        inputs = inputs.to(device)
        feature = model(inputs).squeeze().cpu().numpy()
        features.extend(feature)
        labels.extend(targets.cpu().numpy())
    
    return np.array(features), np.array(labels)


model = models_list['densenet121']

from xgboost import XGBClassifier

def evaluate_classifier(clf, x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test):
    clf.fit(x_train, y_train)
    test_preds = clf.predict(x_test)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, test_preds)
    confusion = confusion_matrix(y_test, test_preds)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, test_preds, average=None)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, test_preds, average=None)
    return accuracy, confusion, precision, recall


classifiers = [XGBClassifier, RandomForestClassifier, SVC]
for classifier in classifiers:
    clf = classifier(n_estimators=50, random_state=3) if classifier.__name__ != 'SVC' else classifier()
    accuracy, confusion, precision, recall = evaluate_classifier(clf, x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test)
    
    print(classifier.__name__)
    print(f"Test accuracy: {accuracy}")
    print(f"Precision: {np.mean(precision)}")
    print(f"Recall: {np.mean(recall)}\n")
    
    classes = test_dataset.classes
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
    sns.set(font_scale=0.8)
    sns.heatmap(confusion, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues", xticklabels=classes, yticklabels=classes)
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Labels')
    plt.ylabel('True Labels')
    plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
    plt.show()
    
    print()
